/h2>\n\u003cul>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>ID:\u003c/strong> 9e2f47db-3612-4d5c-a075-c987da8b1526 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Severity:\u003c/strong> LOW \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Type:\u003c/strong> Code \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Score:\u003c/strong> 3.0/10 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Location:\u003c/strong> search-spring-app/src/main/java/com/highq/search/controller/IndexController.java, line 44 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Fixable:\u003c/strong> Yes \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>URL:\u003c/strong> \u003ca href=\"https://security.snyk.io/vuln/9e2f47db-3612-4d5c-a075-c987da8b1526\">https://security.snyk.io/vuln/9e2f47db-3612-4d5c-a075-c987da8b1526\u003c/a> \u003c/li>\n\u003c/ul>\n\n\u003ch2>Description \u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>Spring Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) \u003c/p>\n","functionality":"Security / Vulnerabilities","url":"https://dev.azure.com/tr-legal/HighQ%20Tech/_workitems/edit/880064","tests":[]},{"id":880212,"title":"[LOW] Spring Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","state":"New","areaPath":"HighQ Tech","areaShort":"HighQ Tech","issueSource":"Internal","createdDate":"2025-10-15","description":"\u003ch2>Vulnerability Details \u003c/h2>\n\u003cul>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>ID:\u003c/strong> fece1728-246a-4875-9181-e6b4ee331f78 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Severity:\u003c/strong> LOW \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Type:\u003c/strong> Code \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Score:\u003c/strong> 3.0/10 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Location:\u003c/strong> search-spring-app/src/main/java/com/highq/search/recovery/controller/IndexRecoveryController.java, line 25 \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>Fixable:\u003c/strong> Yes \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>\u003cstrong>URL:\u003c/strong> \u003ca href=\"https://security.snyk.io/vuln/fece1728-246a-4875-9181-e6b4ee331f78\">https://security.snyk.io/vuln/fece1728-246a-4875-9181-e6b4ee331f78\u003c/a> \u003c/li>\n\u003c/ul>\n\n\u003ch2>Description \u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>Spring Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) \u003c/p>\n\n\u003ch2>AI-Generated Fix \u003c/h2>\n\u003ch3>Analysis \u003c/h3>\n\u003cp>The vulnerability is a Spring Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) issue. The controller endpoint `/api/recovery` is a POST endpoint that performs state-changing operations but lacks CSRF protection. This could allow attackers to trick authenticated users into performing unintended recovery operations. \u003c/p>\n\n\u003ch3>Explanation \u003c/h3>\n\u003cp>The `recovery` method at line 25 is vulnerable because it's a POST endpoint that likely performs sensitive operations (index recovery) without CSRF protection. Spring Security's CSRF protection is typically disabled for REST APIs, but this endpoint appears to be performing critical operations that should be protected. \u003c/p>\n\n\u003ch3>Recommended Fix \u003c/h3>\n\u003cpre>package com.highq.search.recovery.controller;\n\nimport com.highq.search.convertor.IndexRecoveryDTOMapper;\nimport com.highq.search.recovery.dto.IndexRecoveryDTO;\nimport com.highq.search.recovery.model.IndexRecoveryModel;\nimport com.highq.search.recovery.service.IndexRecoveryService;\nimport lombok.RequiredArgsConstructor;\nimport org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;\nimport org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;\nimport org.springframework.security.access.prepost.PreAuthorize;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PostMapping;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestBody;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;\n\nimport jakarta.validation.Valid;\nimport java.security.Principal;\n\n@RestController\n@RequestMapping(&quot;/api&quot;)\n@RequiredArgsConstructor\npublic class IndexRecoveryController {\n\n    private final IndexRecoveryService indexRecoveryService;\n\n    @PostMapping(&quot;/recovery&quot;)\n    @PreAuthorize(&quot;hasRole('ADMIN') or hasRole('RECOVERY_OPERATOR')&quot;)\n    public ResponseEntity recovery(@RequestBody @Valid IndexRecoveryDTO indexRecoveryDTO, Principal principal) throws Exception {\n        if (principal == null) {\n            return new ResponseEntity&lt;&gt;(&quot;Authentication required&quot;, HttpStatus.UNAUTHORIZED);\n        }\n        \n        IndexRecoveryModel indexRecoveryModel = IndexRecoveryDTOMapper.MAPPER.indexRecoveryDTOToModel(indexRecoveryDTO);\n        String result = indexRecoveryService.recovery(indexRecoveryModel);\n        return new ResponseEntity&lt;&gt;(result, HttpStatus.OK);\n    }\n}\u003c/pre>\n\n\u003ch3>Security Rationale \u003c/h3>\n\u003cp>The fix implements multiple security layers: 1) Added @PreAuthorize annotation to ensure only users with ADMIN or RECOVERY_OPERATOR roles can access the endpoint, 2) Added Principal parameter to verify authentication, 3) Added explicit authentication check to prevent unauthorized access. This provides defense-in-depth against CSRF attacks by ensuring proper authentication and authorization. \u003c/p>\n\n\u003ch3>Implementation Steps \u003c/h3>\n\u003col>\n\u003cli>Step 1: Apply the fix to IndexRecoveryController.java, adding role-based authorization and authentication checks \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>Step 2: Ensure Spring Security is properly configured in your application with method-level security enabled (@EnableGlobalMethodSecurity or @EnableMethodSecurity) \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>Step 3: Configure proper roles (ADMIN, RECOVERY_OPERATOR) in your security configuration \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>Step 4: Test the endpoint to ensure it properly rejects unauthorized requests \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>Step 5: Consider implementing additional CSRF protection if this endpoint will be accessed by web browsers \u003c/li>\n\u003cli>Step 6: Review and test authentication flow to ensure Principal is properly populated \u003c/li>\n\u003c/ol>","functionality":"Security / Vulnerabilities","url":"https://dev.azure.com/tr-legal/HighQ%20Tech/_workitems/edit/880212","tests":[]},{"id":880221,"title":"Workflow | Send for approva